We should use the same file storage convention we use for attachments to thumbnails. Currently thumbnails are stored under Confluence Home/thumbnails/pageId/filename format.

We recently ran in to a problem when using the rich text editor to include an image.  The wiki markup that was rendered looked like:

Unknown macro: { return Object.extend.apply(this, [this, object]); } " align="absmiddle" border="0" /> 

Turns out our theme we created is using the prototype library (version 1.3.1) included w/ Confluence 2.2.9.  This has the following code:

Object.prototype.extend = function(object) {
  return Object.extend.apply(this, [this, object]);
}

In editor_plugin_src.js, the following code will add the "extend" function to imageProperties when doing a new Object():

ConfImage.prototype.Ok = function (fileName, thumbnail, alignment, tag, pageId)
{
    if (this.imageProperties == undefined)
    {
        this.imageProperties = new Object();
    }

Obviously we could just grab the latest version, but it would make sense, if you haven't done so already, to upgrade prototype to 1.5.
